*And even a third one
*Because we don't understand the brain very well we're constantly 
tempted to use the latest technology as a model for trying to understand 
it. In my childhood we were always assured that the brain was a 
telephone switchboard. (What else could it be?) And I was amused to see 
that Sherrington, the great British neuroscientist, thought that the 
brain worked like a telegraph system. Freud often compared the brain to 
hydraulic and electromagnetic systems. Leibniz compared it to a mill, 
and now, obviously, the metaphor is the digital computer - John R. 
SEARLE, philosophy professor (b. 1932)

