                    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="3"><br>
                      <b>A thought for today<br>
                      </b>Money often costs too much - Ralph Waldo
                      EMERSON, writer and philosopher (1803-1882)<br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      <b>And a second one<br>
                      </b>The test of our progress is not whether we add
                      more to the abundance of those who have much, it
                      is whether we provide enough for those who have
                      too little - Franklin D. ROOSEVELT, 32nd US
                      President (1882-1945)<br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      <b>And even a third one<br>
                      </b>Because we don't understand the brain very
                      well we're constantly tempted to use the latest
                      technology as a model for trying to understand it.
                      In my childhood we were always assured that the
                      brain was a telephone switchboard. (What else
                      could it be?) And I was amused to see that
                      Sherrington, the great British neuroscientist,
                      thought that the brain worked like a telegraph
                      system. Freud often compared the brain to
                      hydraulic and electromagnetic systems. Leibniz
                      compared it to a mill, and now, obviously, the
                      metaphor is the digital computer - John R. SEARLE,
                      philosophy professor (b. 1932)<br>
                    </font><br>
