                    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="3"><br>
                      <b>Conference on "ICT for Rural Economic
                        Development"<br>
                      </b>18-19 November 2010 (in BERLIN &amp; online) -
                      invitation to participate<br>
                      Eighty high level experts will meet in Berlin to
                      explore the potential of Information and
                      Communication Technologies (ICT) for economic
                      development in rural areas of developing
                      countries. Organized by GTZ on behalf of the
                      Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation and
                      Development (BMZ), the conference participants
                      will debate e-agriculture, ICT business
                      innovation, ICT-backed financial service
                      development, and universal access to ICT
                      infrastructures.<br>
                      <br>
                      They will share project practice and experiences,
                      analyse the impact of ICT policies and
                      regulations, the benefits of ICT for local
                      communities, and investigate innovative business
                      models as well as the impact of new technologies.
                      To review the full list of topics and discussion
                      groups, you can access the agenda at <a
                        href="http://ict.ez-blogs.de/">http://ict.ez-blogs.de/</a>.<br>
                      <br>
                      You are invited to virtually follow the discussion
                      online during the conference, through GTZ&#8217;s ICT4D
                      Blog: <a href="http://ict.ez-blogs.de/and">http://ict.ez-blogs.de/and</a>
                      Twitter using the #ICTGTZ tag. If you wish to
                      comment on the posted summaries, you can register
                      on the blog page. Registration is open to all.<br>
                      <br>
                      The following organizations will participating in
                      the conference: FAO, UNCTAD, InfoDev, CTO, BMZ,
                      BMELV, BMWi, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of
                      Finland, DFID, GTZ, DED, KfW, InWent, Tufts
                      University, , Fraunhofer, University of Siegen,
                      Royal Holloway, IICD, Kabissa, LinkNet Zambia,
                      Kiwanja.net, GSMA, BITKOM, SAP, NSN, Manobi,
                      MicroBanker, Detecon, Intelecon, BIID, etc.<br>
                      <br>
                      The debate will continue online after the
                      conference hosted on the e-Agriculture Community
                      at <a href="http://www.e-agriculture.org/">http://www.e-agriculture.org/</a>
                      from 24 November to 1 December 2010. All
                      e-Agriculture Community members are invited to
                      participate. You can join e-Agriculture by
                      registering free online.<br>
                      <br>
                      See: <a
                        href="http://www.e-agriculture.org/forums/discussions/gtz-discussion">http://www.e-agriculture.org/forums/discussions/gtz-discussion</a><br>
                      See: <a href="http://www.gtz.de/en">http://www.gtz.de/en</a><br>
                      See: <a href="http://www.bmz.de/en">http://www.bmz.de/en</a><br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      Ma remarque (GW) : je ne sais pas si nos
                      organisations fran&ccedil;aises de coop&eacute;ration
                      internationale ont d&eacute;j&agrave; test&eacute; ce genre d'action ?<br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      <b>PARASITEC 2010 (annonce bien tardive&#8230;)<br>
                      </b>17 - 19 novembre 2010 - PARIS<br>
                      - Contexte r&eacute;glementaire de la directive 98/8 et
                      sa mise en oeuvre : point d&#8217;actualit&eacute; (Bureau des
                      Substances et Pr&eacute;parations Chimiques &#8211; MEEDAT)<br>
                      - Point sur les demandes d&#8217;A.M.M. (D. Ambrosi -
                      Ambrosi Scientific Consulting).<br>
                      - Les anticoagulants - rodonticides : les mythes
                      et les r&eacute;alit&eacute;s des intoxications sur le terrain.<br>
                      - La processionnaire du pin : adapter les m&eacute;thodes
                      de r&eacute;gulation en fonction du &laquo; risque &raquo;. J.-C.
                      Martin - Directeur UEF - INRA. Avignon.<br>
                      - La lutte contre les nuisibles en IAA<br>
                      Voir : <a
